# Double Chess Project Rule

## Vision
- Build a fast, tactical chess variant that minimizes opening memorization.
- Optimize for real-time strategic play and clear player feedback.

## Tech Constraints
- Use only Vanilla HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.
- Do not use external frontend frameworks (React, Vue, etc.).
- Do not use chess libraries (such as chess.js).
- Keep game logic and UI/DOM manipulation strictly separated.

## Variant Rules (Must Enforce)
- Use standard chess movement and support en passant, castling, and promotion.
- Allow up to two moves per turn (same piece twice or different pieces).
- If Move 1 gives check, end the turn immediately (no Move 2).
- If a player starts in check, Move 1 must resolve check; Move 2 is only allowed after successful resolution.
- Never allow king movement through or onto attacked squares in either move.

## UI Requirements
- Flip the board 180 degrees with CSS transition after a full turn ends.
- Counter-rotate piece glyphs so they remain upright.
- Add subtle selection/move visual feedback (highlight, scale, etc.).
- Show dual timers (fast-play style) and keep them synchronized with turn state.
- Clearly display active player and whether the turn is on Move 1 or Move 2.
- Ensure responsive playability on both desktop and mobile.

## Security and Validation
- Validate all moves using internal JavaScript game state only.
- Never trust DOM state or raw user input as game truth.
- Keep state shape deterministic and server-verifiable for future anti-cheat backend checks.

## AI Coding Standards
- Never leave placeholder logic (for example, "implement later").
- Implement complete, functional code for requested features.
- For highly complex rule logic, add brief comments explaining decision flow.
